“It’s not China that’s putting sticks in the way of academic leaders, it’s corporations,” Lee said.
Facebook, Google and other tech companies have hired outstanding graduates from universities to work on AI in recent years.
Lee said changes to immigration policy could help the U.S. step up its AI efforts.
“I think we should automatically offer visas to PhD students in AI,” he said.
The State Council of China issued a New Generation of Artificial Intelligence Development Plan in July 2017.
The National Foundation for Natural Sciences in China provides financial support to individuals in academic institutions similar to the way the National Foundation for Science and other government organizations provide money to researchers in the United States, but the quality of academic activity is lower in China, Lee said.
Earlier this year, the U.S. Department of Defense established a Joint Center for Artificial Intelligence to engage industry partners and academics, and the White House announced the formation of an Artificial Intelligence Selection Commission.
This month, the U.S. Army Research Institute (DARPA) announced a $2 billion investment for an initiative called AI Next.
