Macedonians will vote in referendum if they want to change the country's name
Macedonian citizens voted in a referendum on Sunday if they wanted the country's name changed to "Republic of North Macedonia," a change that would resolve a decade-old dispute with Greece, which opposed its accession to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which includes a province called Macedonia, claims the name of the neighboring country represents a claim on its territory and has opposed its accession to the EU and NATO.
The two governments agreed in June on the proposed new name, but opposition nationalists argue that this change would undermine the ethnic identity of the majority Slavic population in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and that a boycott campaign has raised doubts about the voter turnout, and it is possible that the minimum 50% limit required to validate the referendum will not be reached.
The question on the ballot in the referendum will be: “Do you agree to join the EU and NATO, accepting the agreement with Greece?”.
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, say it is a price to pay by Macedonia, one of the countries that resulted from the breakup of Yugoslavia, in order to be accepted in entities such as the EU and NATO.
“I am here today to vote for the future of the country, so that the young people of Macedonia can live free under the umbrella of the European Union, because it means safer lives for all of us,” said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, quite a few members of parliament have said they will respect the result of the vote to make it decisive.
For the name to be changed, a two-thirds quorum in parliament is required.
The state electoral commission said that no irregularities were reported until 13:00.
However, participation was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary election in 2016 when 66% of people with voting rights voted.
“I came to vote for my children and for our place in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter from Skopje, the country’s capital.
On September 30, 2018, Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica, and their son Dushko voted for the referendum on changing the name of Macedonia, which will allow him to join NATO and join the European Union.
In front of the Skopje parliament, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov has prepared a small-scale scene and pulled seats in front of the tents raised by those who will boycott the referendum.
“We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join them with our heads up, not the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not wanted in the name of Macedonia, we can go to other countries, such as China and Russia, and we can become part of the Eurasian Union.”
Prime Minister Zaev said joining NATO would bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has a unemployment rate of more than 20 percent.
“I think the majority will be in favour of changing the name, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of joining NATO and the EU,” Zaev said after voting.
He said a result in favor of changing the name would be “confirming our future.”
According to a poll published last month by the Institute for Policy Research, between 30% and 43% of citizens with voting rights will participate in the referendum, below the required number of participants.
According to another survey conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Seventy percent of them said they would vote for change.
In order for the referendum to be valid, the attendance must be 50% plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum would represent the first serious blow to pro-Western government policy since the government took over in May last year.
