Unfortunately, today, many meetings do not take place in this way, and the promise of a “better, gentler” political environment has long been forgotten, if ever respected.
It has become increasingly evident that different opinions are not tolerated in the Labour Party and that each opinion is judged according to what is accepted by the party leadership.
Things started to be like this when Jeremy became a leader, when I noticed that some colleagues with whom I had a common vision on politics began to expect me to change my mindset and agree with some things I would not have agreed to before, including national security or the EU single market.
Every time I speak in public, no matter what I say, there is a wave of abuses on the desocialization networks that demand my removal from the party, denouncing the center politics, telling me that I should not be in the Labour Party.
And I'm not the only person who's facing this.
Indeed, I know that I am luckier than my colleagues, because comments about my person tend to be political in nature.
I am impressed by the professionalism and determination of my colleagues who face sexual or racist abuse, but maintain their level of involvement in this regard.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this political era is that abuse has become normal.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should adopt a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we no longer accept different views within the party, and with each motion of censorship or change of selection rules, the party becomes less and less flexible on this aspect.
Many people have advised me over the past two years to put my head down, not to be so vocal, and everything will be “okay” like this.
But that's not why I went into politics.
Since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student, motivated by the fact that the negligence of the Thatcher government led to the collapse of my class, I wanted to fight for improved public services for those most in need, as a local councillor or minister.
I have never hid my political opinions, including in the last election.
No one in Nottingham East can say that my views on politics and the issues with which I disagree with the current leadership are unclear.
To the people who supported Friday’s motion, I can only say that in the context of the country’s heading towards Brexit, which will affect our local households, businesses and services, I do not understand their desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But the only message I want to convey is not for the Momentum Group in Nottingham, but for the citizens, whether or not they are members of the Labour Party: I am proud to represent you and I promise you that no threat of removal from the party or political opportunism will stop me from making the decisions that I consider your superior interest in.
Chris Leslie is a member of the Labour Party for Nottingham East
