John Edward: Language Competencies, Essential for Global Citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record for academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional exam results, which is supported by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other community efforts.
With over 30,000 students from Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide services at the highest level to students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for high school and higher education, their chosen career and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a particular school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, your words will reach his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words reach his heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year’s competition, we note that foreign languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest rates of promotion within independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained a Higher Grade A certificate.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of students obtained a Higher Grade A certificate in Mandarin; also 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French and 63% of those studying Spanish obtained such a certificate.
This demonstrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Now, foreign languages, as subjects, are held in the same way as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and in other fields.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that for reasons employers gave for the struggle for vacancies, 17% were attributed to a language skills deficit.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly imperative for preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities requiring foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future, having such a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person before the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15%.
That’s why investing in foreign language learning is important for children today.
With more languages, especially in developing economies, children will have a greater chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach other foreign languages.
A number of schools will focus on more modern classical languages, while others will learn languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be more languages of choice within independent schools, with teaching staff who are specialized in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and encourage them with the skills necessary to succeed, whatever the future may be.
It cannot be denied at this time, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be vital for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should indeed be considered “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done (it has to be done).
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
