North Korea says there is “no chance” of disarming unilaterally as long as there is no trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that extending sanctions would deepen distrust in the United States and that it is impossible for his country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the Global Council that "significant measures to prove their good faith" were implemented in North Korea last year, such as halting nuclear testing and missile testing, dismantling the nuclear testing site and the commitment to non-proliferation of weapons.
"However, we do not see any appropriate response from the United States," he said.
"If we can't trust the United States, we won't trust our national security capabilities, and under such circumstances, we can't unilaterally disarm ourselves first."
Although Ri resumed familiar objections by North Korea to Washington’s counter-resistance to a “standardized” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded if it took gradual steps, his statement seemed significant because it did not directly reject the unilateral past denuclearization.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at a first-ever summit between a U.S. president and North Korea's leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to make progress towards "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula," while Trump offered North Korea security assurances.
North Korea sought an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington has not heeded calls for a relaxation of the harsh international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
“The United States insists on the option of ‘denuclearization first’ and increases the pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, and even objects to the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The impression that sanctions can kneel is an illusion that only people who don’t know us have.
But the problem is that prolonged sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader referred to at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae-in, the president of South Korea, over the past five months, adding: "If the issue of denuclearization had been negotiated with South Korea and not with the US, this denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have been successful."
Even under these conditions, the tone of Ri's speech was very different from last year's, when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting U.S. territory with missiles from North Korea was inevitable after "Mr. President Trump" called Kim a "missile-man" in his speech.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who had threatened North Korea with “total destruction” last year, praised Kim for the courage to begin the disarmament process, but said the work was just beginning and that sanctions would remain in place until North Korea was denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no planned period for this and added: “It doesn’t matter if it takes two or three years or five months.”
China and Russia say Pyongyang should be rewarded by the UN Security Council for the measures taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without interruption until we achieve complete, final and confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions imposed on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to block funds for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the last visit did not have very good results.
When he left Pyongyang in July, he said progress had been made, but after only a few hours, North Korea denounced him as a "gangster threat."
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile launch pad and a nuclear complex if the United States takes “appropriate action.”
He said Kim told him that the "appropriate measures" he was looking for were the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and that he wanted normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take classes on how to get enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year encourages students to sleep longer, in an attempt to combat the growing “macho” culture that makes them submit to “all-night” high-caffeine-energetic learning sessions.
A scientist has discovered that often, students at the world’s most prestigious university do not even master the basic concepts of how they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the one who created the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to create the course after holding a lecture on the impact of lack of sleep on the ability to learn.
“In the end, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told this now, in the last year?’
She told me that she had never been told about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, introduced for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course may involve a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, the image of a home room is presented, and students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports pants and books to tell them what the effects of caffeine and light are and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, but also about the importance of a sleep program.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily schedule.
“We know we can’t immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture that makes students proud that they’ve learned all night long still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure on students have turned sleep deprivation into a growing problem.
Adequate, good quality sleep should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, as sleep deprivation makes the brain believe the body is hungry, making students feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after attending one of his courses in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to require all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before enrolling in this institution where the competition is fierce.
Professor Czeisler recommended students to schedule an alarm to know when it is time to go to bed, as well as for waking time, and to know what are the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause difficulties when we wake up.
