And now, a page from our Almanac on Sunday morning: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago (and the count CONTINUOUS...), is the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the creation of the device known as the Geiger counter.
An essential device for science ever since, the Geiger counter has also become essential for pop culture, as happened in the film "The Bells of San Coronado" (1950), in which Roy Rogers and Dale Evans played the role of cowboys with unlikely inclinations toward science:
Man: “What’s that?”
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals, like uranium.
When you wear these headphones, you can hear the effects of atoms emitted by radioactivity in minerals.”
Evans: “Yes, you can hear a lot of knocks!”
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name is still alive.
