Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley Feels ‘Inferior’ to Sexuality
Olympic diver Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to everyone because of his sexuality, but this motivated him to succeed.
The 24-year-old said he only realized when he got to school that “not everyone is like me.”
Invited to Lauren Laverne’s first Desert Island Discs show on Radio 4, he said he was talking about gay people’s rights to give others “hope.”
The athlete also said that when he became a parent, he cared less about the Olympics.
Kirsty Young, the regular presenter of the traditional show, will be missing a few months due to a disease.
Invited to the first edition presented by Laverne, Daley said that when he was a child he felt "lower" than others because "it was socially unacceptable for me to like boys and girls as well."
He said: “Until now, these feelings of inferiority and the fact that I felt different, it was the real things that gave me the strength and endurance to achieve success.”
He wanted to prove he was “someone,” he said, so he wouldn’t disappoint everyone when they finally found out about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic gold medalist became a well-known supporter of LGBT campaigns and took advantage of his appearance at this year’s Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he decided to talk because he felt lucky to be able to live free, with no consequences, and because he wanted to give others “hope.”
The three-time world champion said he was "surprised" by the fact that he fell in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black.
Daley married the Oscar-winning filmmaker, who is 20 years older than him, but said the age difference was never an issue.
“When you’re going through so much at such a young age,” he said at the first Olympics when he was just 14 and his father died of cancer after three years, he said, “it’s hard to find someone of the same age who’s been through the same good and bad times.”
The two became parents in June to a boy named Robert Ray Black-Daley, which, Daley says, changed his “whole perspective.”
“If I had been asked last year, I wouldn’t have been interested in anything other than winning a gold medal,” he said.
“You know what? There are more important things than gold medals at the Olympics.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie."
His son is named after his father, Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father did not accept that he was going to die and that one of the last things he wanted was to find out if they had received tickets to the 2012 London Olympics because he wanted to be first.
“I couldn’t say to him, ‘You won’t be able to be first, Dad,’” he said.
“I held his hand when he stopped breathing and only after he stopped breathing and died I finally accepted that he was not invincible,” he said.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympic Games and won the bronze medal.
"I knew that I dreamed of a lifetime of jumping in front of my country's spectators at the Olympics, there's no better feeling," he said.
This also inspired him in his chosen music, Heather Small's Proud, a song that encouraged him before the Olympics and still excites him.
Desert Island Discs is broadcast on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15.
