Germany's new warship postponed again
Germany’s newest naval frigate should have been put into operation in 2014 to replace the outdated Cold War warships, but this will only happen next year, due to flawed systems and rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the new Baden-Württemberg frigate class, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper, quoting a military spokesman.
The vessel was supposed to be introduced to the maritime forces in 2014, but problems that arose after delivery affected this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
It is assumed that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, with a range of anti-aircraft and anti-tank missiles, as well as stealth technologies, which ensure a reduced radar, infrared and acoustic footprint.
Other important features will include longer maintenance periods; it should be possible for new frigates to be able to depart for two-year missions without returning to their original port.
However, the ongoing delays mean that these state-of-the-art warships, which are said to boost Germany’s maritime strength, will already be obsolete before they enter service, Die Zeit notes.
The F125 frigate was discussed in the press last year when the German Navy officially refused to take over the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned a ship to the builder after delivery.
Not much information is available on the reasons for the refusal, but the German media cited a number of crucial "software and hardware flaws" that would have made the warship useless in a combat mission.
The software flaws were particularly significant because the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships would be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, only half of the crews on the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the ship was too heavy, which reduced its performance and limited the Navy's ability to add future equipment.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz vessel is believed to be twice as heavy as the ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the defective mechanisms, the cost of the entire project, including that of training the crew, has become a cause for concern.
It is said to have reached an astonishing 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) from the initial price of 2.2 billion euros.
The problems of the newest frigates are of particular importance given the latest warnings that Germany’s maritime power is declining.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, the head of the defence committee in the German parliament, acknowledged that the Navy "began to run out of vessels that can be sent on missions."
The official said the problem has steadily increased over time as old vessels have been taken out of service without being replaced with new ones.
He lamented the fact that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class entered service within the Navy.
National Trust spying on the secret life of bats
New research that is being conducted on a property in the Scottish Highlands wants to reveal how bats use the environment to hunt their prey.
It is hoped that the findings will reveal new things about the behavior of these new flying mammals and will help future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland, will analyze common dwarf bats and pygmy bats, as well as eared bats and water bats from the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed in key locations around the property to track the activity of bats throughout the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
Specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by bats and what species emit certain sounds.
A habitat map and a report will also be produced to create a detailed, scaled-up picture of their behaviour in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas in the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of lawns, and what is the best way to maintain forest pastures for bats and other associated species.
Populations of bats in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably in the last century.
They are endangered by construction and development work that affects their nests, as well as habitat loss.
Both wind turbines and public lighting are risks, as are fly traps and some chemical treatments for building materials, as well as domestic cat attacks.
Actually, bats aren't blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, thinks very seriously about bats.
They have ten trained experts, who periodically conduct studies, control nests, and sometimes carry out rescue missions.
The organization has created even the first and only bat reserve in Scotland, on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight out of ten species of bat are found in Scotland.
The estate manager, David Thompson, says this is the ideal territory for bats.
“Here at Threave, the area is great for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there are a lot of things we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand why they need to multiply.”
It emphasizes the importance of looking for bats before carrying out maintenance work at properties, since the simple unintentional destruction of a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and chicks, which can destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected, and killing, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are prohibited actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help them.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and we don’t know how populations evolve for many of our species.”
