Fishing and farming activities represent the central point of the province’s economy in the centre of Sulawesi Island, in particular the Donggala coastal region.
Nickel mining activities are also important in the province, but are concentrated mainly in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi Island.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times over the past 100 years, according to Indonesia's Disaster Management Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
Also in 1996, a tsunami struck the western part of the Donggala regency, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Circle of Fire, an area with intense seismic activity.
Here are some of the earthquakes and tsunamis that have occurred in recent years:
2004: On December 26, a powerful earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Aceh province, north of Sumatra Island, triggered a tsunami that hit 14 countries, killing 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them from Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people have died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake on the Richter scale hit the south of Indonesia's most populous island, Java, triggering a tsunami that hit the south coast, killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake on the Richter scale occurred near the city of Padang, the capital of West Sumatra province.
