Red tide news: concentrations have fallen in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The Florida Wildlife Protection Commission’s latest report shows a general drop in red tide concentrations for certain areas of the Tampa Bay.
According to the Commission, uneven inflorescence conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting lower concentrations.
This red tide inflorescence extends over a coast area of approximately 210 km, from Pinellas County north to Lee County south.
The spots can be found about 10 miles (16 km) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
The average concentrations found in Pinellas County or off the coast of Charlotte County were reported last week, as well as low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, background concentrations to high in Manatee County, background concentrations to high in Sarasota County or off the coast of Charlotte County, background concentrations to high in Manatee County, background concentrations to high in Sarasota County or off the coast of Charlotte County.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No cases of airway irritation have been reported in the northwestern state of Florida in the past week.
